.<br>
<br>
Anyway, if you're new to this, it's simple:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> THE GREAT MAGICIAN'S GALA</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
A no-holds-barred exhibition of spellcasting, as an annual fair coincides with a secret quest for a powerful heirloom.<br>
<br>
Entrants can choose to be a mage (your standard magician), a sage (your crochety old wizards) or a warrior mage (which is a silly term, since even a typical magician can use a sword or shield; &quot;warrior&quot; mages just use their weapons <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> with proficiency &amp; expertise </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->)<br>
and any discipline of magic is welcome.<br>
NOTE: A mage is just another term for a magician, but a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> sorcerer/sorceress</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> is someone with a born knack for magic-- thus they don't need a book of spells (but this also means their arsenal is very limited.)  Conversely, a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> wizard/warlock/witch</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> has a HUGE library of spells (so they can pull out a truckload of surprise spells!), but can't always remember them and/or can only use a spell once or twice in a day (whereas a sorcerer could use the same spell a LOT more often.)<br>
Sorcerer = more power, less spells<br>
Wizard = more spells, less power<br>
<br>
Included here are some good examples of disciplines &amp; some limits:<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> conjuration</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Casting fireballs &amp; summoning lightning storms, the conjurer is the de-facto magician.  Not much on technique when compared to other mages, but who needs technique when you can immoliate your opponents or freeze their bodies in stone!<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> summoning</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Raising familiars, beasts &amp; monsters to do the work; the stronger the beast, the harder to summon-- a Bahamut style summon is the realm of summoning MASTERS.<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> enchantment</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Mind control or charming foes, as well as causing paralyzing fear or even making one's limbs &amp; organs attack their attached body!!  Your weapon is your opponent's own mind &amp; body!<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> illusionists</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> making the impossible <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> seem</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> possible.  And making it hard for the enemy to tell what's real &amp; what's not!  A good illusionist supports their own skills in melee combat-- or lack thereof-- with enough trickery to take the fight out of their opponent!<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> necromancy</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Raise the dead!  Command the dark!<br>
Necromancers use the black arts of curses, arcane sorcery &amp; worse to destroy their opponents.  Voodoo &amp; some tenants of astrology might come into play when sealing a mortal's fate with a curse...<br>
<br>
-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> elemental</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Here, it's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> three positive elements</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> -- earth, wind, water; <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> their negative opposites</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> -- fire, lightning, ice; weaknesses run in this cycle of order (from strong-to-weak against, L. to R.):<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fire-- wind-- ice-- earth-- lightning-- water-- fire</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
so, fire mages can wipe out wind mages, but water mages can defeat fire mages, and so on.  Complimenting elements are:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fire = earth</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> lightning = wind</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> ice = water</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
so a fire mage &amp; an earth mage is an automatic stalemate-- neither can hurt each other!  You can't specialize in two differing disciplines like ice &amp; fire (they won't interact &amp; all spells would fizzle out), but two separate mages with complimenting elements can have some wild effects...<br>
<br>
Bearing in mind most mages at least know enough to haul around a staff, a wand or a knife, the proficient warrior mages with swords, martial arts &amp; the like <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> can't</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> use them exclusively; here, it's the spell that rules over the sword.<br>
(I know *I* won't.)<br>
Also, they can be of any class, race, species, etc., so if you have a catgirl sorceress or a spellslinging ogre, I'll allow it!<br>
<br>
As for characters themselves, I'm limiting all entrants to just one mage per person.  I'm showing three here, as they all have bearing on what's going on (and might show up occasionally to cheer their partner on), but only ONE is going to do the fighting.<br>
My entry is one of the three notorious &quot;Demon Mages&quot;, local to the city where this &quot;Great Magician's Gala&quot; is held.<br>
As to who will be <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> my</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> champion of the three... you'll see.<br>
<br>
Anyone interested?<br>
